==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Grig
<hw>Grig</hw> <pr>(gr⟦icr⟧g)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. Sw.
<ets>kr⟦aum⟧k</ets> little creature, reptile; or D. <ets>kriek</ets>
cricket, E. <ets>cricket</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>
<sd>(a)</sd> <def>A cricket or grasshopper.</def> <mark>[Prov.
Eng.]</mark> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>Any small eel.</def> <sd>(c)</sd>
<def>The broad-nosed eel. See <er>Glut</er>.</def> <mark>[Prov.
Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Heath.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark>
<rj><au>Audrey.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>As merry as a grig</b></col><cd> <ety>[etymology
uncertain]</ety>, a saying supposed by some to be a corruption of
⟦ldquo⟧As merry as a Greek; ⟦rdquo⟧ by others, to be an allusion to the
cricket.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>gri-gri</ent>⟦br⟧
